06:30.840 --> 06:38.580
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Each year, Terry Carr edits two of the
best-known anthologies in science fiction. One is the Universe series, begun in

06:38.580 --> 06:45.780
1971, which is an anthology of original science fiction. We asked Carr the
difference to an author between selling his story to a monthly science fiction

06:45.780 --> 06:50.780
magazine or selling it to an anthology like Universe. There are all sorts of
differences.

06:54.180 --> 07:03.400
They're both artistic and monetary differences. For one thing, if you sell to a
magazine, then the money that you get from the magazine is simply the payment

07:03.400 --> 07:15.180
for that use of the story. If you sell it to an original anthology, that's going
into a book, and you get an advance payment. But after that, you get a share of

07:15.180 --> 07:24.140
the royalties. If the book sells well, then there will be additional earnings on
the book. And the individual authors will continue to make money for years

07:24.140 --> 07:35.560
thereafter, and indeed they do on Universe, because it does sell pretty well. So
your chances of making money on your story are at least as good, I would say, in

07:35.560 --> 07:46.380
the original anthologies as they are in the science fiction magazines. Aside
from that, there's also the fact that a lot of writers simply like to have their

07:46.380 --> 07:57.500
work appear in book form, because they know it's going to be around to be read
longer than a magazine will be. It'll stay in better shape, and it'll be in

07:57.500 --> 07:59.000
libraries and things like that.

08:07.100 --> 08:14.780
The best science fiction of the year, which Carr began in 1972 with Donald
Walheim, is a different sort of anthology. It consists of stories published in

08:14.780 --> 08:21.720
science fiction magazines during the year. Carr reads all the magazines, then
selects those stories he considers to be the best. But he says that there are

08:21.720 --> 08:28.300
certain problems that he has to solve when he actually starts putting the
stories together. I do want to be sure that there aren't too many stories that

08:28.300 --> 08:36.560
are downbeat and depressing, because that's just not fun to read. They may be
good stories individually, but you just string them all end to end, and they can

08:36.560 --> 08:47.900
actually seem not as good as they are. So I try to work on that kind of balance,
and I try to mix up the balance between longer stories and shorter stories,

08:48.340 --> 08:59.560
because people do like variety in that. And if it should ever happen, for
instance, I think the best 15 stories of the year, however many it takes, are

08:59.560 --> 09:08.400
all time travel stories, for instance. I'm not going to publish a whole book
full of time travel stories. That's just silly. Again, people would get tired of

09:08.400 --> 09:20.060
reading so many time travel stories in one book. So I try to mix up the themes,
too. Carr explains the particular needs an anthology fulfills. As best I know,

09:20.220 --> 09:32.040
an anthology fills a need for people who want to read good science fiction short
stories, novelettes, novellas, whatever. People who want to read something other

09:32.040 --> 09:41.280
than a novel. Probably people who want to have something that they can dip into
from time to time, rather than sitting down and reading the whole thing straight

09:41.280 --> 09:50.240
through, as they would a novel. There's a different psychology between reading
novels and short stories, and most people do prefer to read novels. They always

09:50.240 --> 10:02.360
sell better than anthologies or single-author short story collections. But there
are people who like the short stories. I do, for instance. And they're the

10:02.360 --> 10:12.960
people who buy these. On a repaint anthology, the attraction, I think, is that
these stories have been doubly screened. They're stories that were good enough

10:12.960 --> 10:22.460
in the first place to sell to the magazine. And then beyond that, they are the
best stories from the magazine. So the people who pick up an anthology can

10:22.460 --> 10:30.000
reasonably expect that that is going to contain more good stories than the
average issue of a science fiction magazine. This isn't always true. There are

10:30.000 --> 10:39.060
some very bad anthologies, and there are some very good issues of magazines. But
by and large, that is the case, I think. Terry Carr also writes fine science

10:39.060 --> 10:41.660
fiction. Next time, we'll talk to him about some of his own writing.

