12:12.800 --> 12:20.060
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Among the science fiction anthologies that
Terry Carr has edited over the years are the so-called specialized anthologies.

12:20.340 --> 12:28.120
These would be volumes of short stories with a particular theme uniting them.
For example, a book of short stories on robots or time travel. Carr has done

12:28.120 --> 12:36.440
many special anthologies. We spoke with him about a few of them. He explains the
rationale behind his 1966 anthology, Science Fiction for People Who Hate Science

12:36.440 --> 12:49.640
Fiction. That was my first anthology that I did under my own name and nobody
else's name. It was, I think, in fact, the second anthology I did right after it

12:49.640 --> 12:58.240
was the first world's best science fiction. And the idea on it was I wanted a
book that could be given to people who don't normally read science fiction, who

12:58.240 --> 13:10.320
think that they wouldn't like it. And I wanted, first, that the stories should
be good stories. And second, that the stories should be accessible to people who

13:10.320 --> 13:19.160
don't know the specialized language of science fiction. There are a whole lot of
assumptions that are just automatic in science fiction, and nobody bothers to

13:19.160 --> 13:26.160
explain them anymore. And so there are a lot of stories that are published these
days that really require a certain amount of background in reading science

13:26.160 --> 13:34.100
fiction in order to understand them. I mean, nobody stops to explain what a star
warp drive is anymore, because that gets a little bit tiresome after a while. We

13:34.100 --> 13:45.900
all know how a star warp drive works, more or less, or at least we think we do.
But to somebody who's never heard of that before, that can be kind of confusing.

13:46.460 --> 13:52.200
Or the intricacies of the

13:52.200 --> 14:06.760
moralities of robot behavior, or the strangeness of time paradoxes. Things like
that can be very confusing to someone first coming to science fiction. So the

14:06.760 --> 14:16.920
stories that I chose for that book were stories that had very simple, dramatic
ideas, that were very easy to understand to someone who was not used to science

14:16.920 --> 14:25.940
fiction right away, but that were also very good stories. A more recent
anthology is one carded for the Sierra Club, entitled Dream's Edge, Science

14:25.940 --> 14:34.840
Fiction Stories About the Planet Earth. The origin of that was that the Sierra
Club themselves decided they wanted to publish a science fiction anthology. And

14:34.840 --> 14:46.200
they looked around for someone to do it, and they eventually landed on me. The
main problem I had with that book was that there were too many stories in it

14:46.200 --> 14:52.700
that were downbeat and depressing. If you start writing about the ecology of
Earth, which is what the theme of that was,

14:55.560 --> 15:04.120
well, everything's going wrong these days, as you know. And nobody really has
any answers about what we can do about it. So even though I think all the

15:04.120 --> 15:14.120
stories in there are very good, there are only a few of them that hold out a
whole lot of hope. Most of them are about the problems and the ironies of

15:14.120 --> 15:24.060
messing around with the environment and so on. In 1978, Carr put together an
anthology many people consider his finest. It's called Classic Science Fiction,

15:24.180 --> 15:32.800
The First Golden Age. For this one, Carr chose stories from the years 1940 and
1942, a critical time in the development of modern science fiction. While Carr

15:32.800 --> 15:42.740
selected stories, he did something else that makes the volume of particular
interest. But at the same time, I also did a lot of research on the writers, on

15:42.740 --> 15:50.940
the editors, the publishing companies, the artists, and so forth. The conditions
under which they worked, how much money they were actually able to make. And I

15:50.940 --> 16:00.000
wrote a great deal of introductory material, background material, about the
writers and what they were doing, how they came to write each individual story.

16:00.360 --> 16:11.280
And I think the anthology itself contains a number of just classic stories. It's
a basic anthology for anybody's science fiction library. But in addition to

16:11.280 --> 16:20.140
that, that background material is fascinating. It tells a whole lot of things
about how things happened and why they happened. And it also tells a number of

16:20.140 --> 16:28.860
pretty amusing stories about things that went on behind the scenes. I really
enjoyed doing the book. We'll have more with Terry Carr next time.

