18:09.580 --> 18:18.140
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Editor and author Terry Carr has published
three science fiction novels. The first two, Warlord of Kor and Invasion from

18:18.140 --> 18:26.600
2500, go back to the early 1960s and are potboilers in the pulp tradition. But
his most recent novel is a different thing entirely. It's a tightly constructed

18:26.600 --> 18:35.400
work with symbolic and allegorical depth. Entitled Cirque, it was published in
1977. Carr tells us where the idea for the book originated. Cirque is actually

18:35.400 --> 18:48.640
the Bay Area, in some sense anyway, not literally. But the fact is that I live
in the hills of Oakland, in the East Bay. And there's a drive along the ridge of

18:48.640 --> 19:02.320
the hills. And I was up there one evening just at dusk, when the light is such
that the bay itself, which you can look down on, and you'll see San Francisco

19:02.320 --> 19:13.960
and Marin County across the bay, and San Jose to the south, and Berkeley and
Oakland in front of you, and a lot of water in the middle. But at a particular

19:13.960 --> 19:23.340
time of evening, that water simply turned black. And I was up there looking at
that, and I thought, my God, you can't even tell at the bay, it looks like a

19:23.340 --> 19:33.540
gigantic hole in the ground. And immediately I thought, what would a city be
like if it would build around a gigantic shaft into the earth like that? What

19:33.540 --> 19:40.820
effect might that kind of physical environment have on the psychology of the
people who lived in that city?

19:47.860 --> 19:55.260
Carr explores the psychology and destiny of various inhabitants of the city,
Sirk, during an unusual day's occurrences. On that day, some monsters rise out

19:55.260 --> 20:02.340
of the abyss the city is built around. The monsters are huge and ominous, and
the reaction of Carr's characters to them forms the basis of the book. Near the

20:02.340 --> 20:10.040
end of the novel, the monsters, after threatening the inhabitants of Sirk, turn
into flowers. This episode, along with many others in the book, suggests a

20:10.040 --> 20:19.080
symbolic intent on Carr's part. We asked him if there was deliberate symbolism
in the book. Oh yes, that is definitely the most important. I knew the general

20:19.080 --> 20:30.500
outline of the story. I just didn't know the specifics of who was going to do
what at which time and where they were going to be, and so on. The symbolism is

20:30.500 --> 20:43.600
built into the whole concept of the story. And I tried not to make that show too
much on the top. I wanted the surface to be a story that was interesting in and

20:43.600 --> 20:52.140
of itself, because I don't believe that symbolism itself should ever try to
carry a story. That bores me to tears. On the other hand, if you have a good

20:52.140 --> 21:05.060
story up front, and beneath that story is symbolism, preferably emotional
symbolism, not just intellectual cuteness, I think that strengthens the story a

21:05.060 --> 21:05.540
good deal.

21:15.440 --> 21:25.980
Carr explains why he chose the title, Cirque, for the novel. The book, of
course, is about a city which is built around a gigantic chasm into the ground.

21:27.600 --> 21:42.600
And so the city is named Cirque, which is French for circle, and has other
connotations too. It also, for instance, it's the French word for circus. And it

21:42.600 --> 21:55.620
was kind of a circus. There were a whole lot of things, strange things going on
at once in the book. And the construction of the book is circular. It starts at

21:55.620 --> 22:07.120
dawn on one day, and it goes ahead to finish at dawn the next day. And it
finishes at the same place in the city where it began, with the same characters

22:07.120 --> 22:18.160
there. So in all those ways, Cirque or circle was the perfect title for the
book. The only thing it really had going against it is that nobody knows how to

22:18.160 --> 22:21.980
pronounce it. We'll have more from Terry Carr next time.

